Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/tabledOn
Object: Relates an act of tabling to the date on which it happened.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/TablingOrWithdrawal
Object: The act of tabling into, or withdrawing a tabled thing from, a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/Tabling
Object: The act of tabling a business item into either the House of Commons or House of Lords. Tabling is the act of formally putting forward a question, a motion, an amendment or a committee membership nomination. Members do this by submitting it to procedural clerks. The item will then appear in the next day's business papers as a written notice. Each House has a Table Office where parliamentary questions, motions for debate and, in the Commons, early day motions are tabled. Amendments to bills are always tabled in the Public Bill Offices of each House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/WrittenNotice
Object: Official notice of an item of future business.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/Withdrawal
Object: The act of withdrawing a tabled thing from a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/givesNotice
Object: Relates an act of tabling to a written notice.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/tables
Object: Relates an act of tabling to the business item which it tables.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/withdraws
Object: Relates an act of withdrawal to the business item which it withdraws.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/House
Object: A parliamentary House, for example: the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/hasHouse
Object: Relates an act of tabling or withdrawal to the House in which it happens.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/withdrawnOn
Object: Relates an act of withdrawal to the date on which it happened.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/TabledThing
Object: Any item of business which has been tabled, for example: a motion, parliamentary question, amendment or committee membership nomination. Note not all things that can be tabled must be tabled, for example: manuscript amendments are amendments which are raised on the day the business occurs. In other words, no notice has been given. For this reason they do not appear on the day's business papers and are rarely selected for debate. Manuscript amendments do not appear on the marshalled list.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/tabledBy
Object: Relates a tabling to the seat incumbency of the Member tabling.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/inSession
Object: Relates an act of tabling or withdrawal to the session in which it happens.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/WithdrawnThing
Object: A tabled thing which has subsequently been withdrawn.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/SeatIncumbency
Object: The occupation of a seat in a House by a person, for a period of time.  A person may have more than one incumbency over time. Only one person can be incumbent in a house seat at one time. A person having a seat incumbency which has a start date in the past and an end date in the future - or which has no end date - is a current Member. A person having a seat incumbency with an end date in the past - and no current incumbency - is an ex-Member.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/replaces
Object: Relates a tabled thing to the withdrawn thing it replaces.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/
Object: A model describing the activity of Members tabling parliamentary questions, motions, amendments and nominations.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/tabling/Session
Object: The period during which Parliament is convened. The first session of a parliament begins on the same day as the parliament period: this date is given in the dissolution proclamation at the end of the previous parliament. The session ends on the day set in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the parliament period begin and end on dates set in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The last session of a parliament ends with prorogation followed by dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.
